## At a Glance

**What's working:** You've built a genuinely novel multi-agent system with mayor/deacon roles, structured patrol loops, and session handoffs — that's production-grade thinking about agent continuity. Your lean-context philosophy with @-linking (getting system prompts down to ~195 tokens) is a creative approach to token management that most users never consider. You also have strong simplification instincts, like condensing 68 Bitwarden files to 3 or tracing a false-alert bug to zsh aliases mangling return codes. See _Impressive Things You Did_.

**What's hindering you:** On Claude's side, it repeatedly jumps into action with wrong assumptions — writing code when you want design, brute-force exploring files when context is already available, and giving confidently wrong explanations it doubles down on. On your side, your Dolt and beads infrastructure is fragile enough that a large chunk of your sessions get entirely consumed by database corruption and initialization failures before the actual patrol work even starts, which means Claude is spending your time on repair loops instead of the tasks you care about. See _Where Things Go Wrong_.

